<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06094284 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06094284 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo, chart; PHOTO: (Anne Small)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PLANT; HEALTH; GUIDELINE; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  For Anne Small, the secrets to good health can be found scattered along thefreeways and seen poking through front yards.;    Mostly ignored and oftentaken for granted, they are the wildflowers and herbs that Small believes helpnurture and heal the human body.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  The Weekly  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HERBS FOR HEALTH ARE VERY EASY PICKINGSSOME WILDFLOWERS MAY HAVE WHAT YOU NEED  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Chart attached to the end of this article  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;I call it the fifth basic food group,&quot; Small says with adamant conviction.&quot;Plants were put here for a reason. They all serve a purpose.&quot;;    Small, 57,shares her holistic approach to health and healing in an eight-session classoffered through the Fremont recreation department. And, beginning next week,in Newark for the first time.;    The owner of a nutritional counselingbusiness and an employee of a Fremont natural food store, Small has devotedher life to teaching the healing benefits of herbs.;    &quot;When I got sick about10 years ago, I did not want to take the medication the doctors were givingme, so I took herbs,&quot; she recalls. &quot;In three days, my symptoms were gone.&quot;;   Afterward, Small began taking classes in herbal remedies which lead to thestudy of other holistic practices such as iridology, which is based on thebelief that weaknesses in one's health can be detected by looking at the irisof the eye.;    Small is careful to point out that in her classes or in herpractice, she does not diagnose or treat people.;    &quot;Herbs should be used forprevention, not for curing diseases,&quot; she says. &quot;I do what I can to keep meand my family healthy, the rest is up to a doctor.&quot;;    Although Small growsmost of her herbs in her own garden behind her Newark home, many plants can befound in the wild. Dandelions and Yellow Dock, which Small calls &quot;bloodpurifiers,&quot; crop up in many front lawns and along Bay Area roadways.;    SinceSmall began teaching her class five years ago, she says interest in herbalremedies and holistic medicine has grown considerably.;    &quot;Our whole cultureis not into healing oneself, but letting someone else do it for us,&quot; she says.&quot;I think people are beginning to realize how crazy that is.&quot;; Herbal remedies;Listed below are some common herbs and uses.; Herb           Use; Fenugreek     Helps relieve colds or sinus ailments; Echinacia      Helps strengthenimmune system; Peppermint     Aids digestive problems; Ginseng       Revitalizes and helps strengthen immune system; Valerian root   Relaxes andaids in sleep; Evening primrose  Eases menstrual discomfort; Source: AnneSmall;  IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The eight-session herbal remedies class inNewark begins Thursday, April 11 from 7:30 to 9 p.m. at the Newark AdultSchool, 36120 Ruschin Drive in Newark. The cost is $35. Call 794-2039 forregistration information.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  FERNANDO QUINTERO, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910403  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO; CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  452  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday April 3, 199100094284,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>